explanation.en:
This patient with ATRIAL FIBRILLATION (irregularly irregular pulse, tachycardia) has isolated left lower extremity motor deficits, most likely caused by a CARDIOEMBOLIC STROKE in the right anterior cerebral artery (ACA) territory. The ACA supplies the medial aspects of the frontal and parietal lobes, a region which contains the upper motor neurons responsible for contralateral lower extremity motor control. Occlusion of the ACA characteristically causes CONTRALATERAL LOWER LIMB WEAKNESS with upper motor neuron signs (eg, hyperreflexia, Babinski sign). Contralateral sensory deficits occur in a minority of patients.

The most common etiology of ACA stroke is cardiac embolization due to Atrial fibrillation, which can cause blood flow stasis resulting in thrombus formation in the left atrial appendage. Atrial thromboemboli frequently travel to and obstruct branches of ACA or middle cerebral artery (MCA), causing cerebral ischemia with associated neurologic defects. {{exhibit_2}}

(Choice A) An embolic occlusion of the anterior spinal artery in the lumbosacral region would cause bilateral lower extremity weakness with hyporeflexia (ischemia of the anterior horns and corticospinal tracts) and loss of pain and temperature sensation (ischemia of the spinothalamic tracts) below the level of the lesion.

(Choice B) Posterior inferior cerebellar artery occlusion characteristically causes ischemia in the lateral medulla (Wallenberg syndrome) and inferior cerebellar peduncle, resulting in dysphagia, hoarseness, and vestibulocerebellar symptoms (eg, ataxia, dizziness, nystagmus). {{exhibit_3}}

(Choice C) Although lumbosacral neural foraminal stenosis can cause unilateral lower extremity weakness, compression injury of a spinal nerve root (lower motor neuron fibers) at this level would typically result in significant radicular back and leg pain with hyporeflexia.

(Choice E) MCA strokes predominantly affect the upper extremity and are often associated with homonymous hemianopia, aphasia, and hemineglect. Although large MCA strokes can also cause lower extremity weakness, the defects in those cases are usually extensive and involve both the upper and lower extremities (hemiparesis). {{exhibit_4}}

explanation.zh:
该患者患有房颤（脉搏不规则，心动过速），表现为左下肢孤立的运动功能障碍，最有可能由右侧大脑前动脉（ACA）区域的栓塞性卒中引起。大脑前动脉供应额叶和顶叶的内侧部分，该区域包含负责对侧下肢运动控制的上运动神经元。大脑前动脉的闭塞典型地导致对侧下肢无力，伴有上运动神经元体征（例如，反射亢进，Babinski征阳性）。对侧感觉障碍仅发生在少数患者中。

大脑前动脉卒中最常见的病因是由于房颤引起的血栓栓塞，这会导致血流淤滞，从而导致血栓形成于左心耳。房性血栓栓塞物经常会转移并阻塞大脑前动脉或大脑中动脉（MCA）的分支，引起脑缺血，并伴有相关的神经功能障碍。{{exhibit_2}}

（选项A）腰骶部脊髓前动脉的栓塞性闭塞会导致双侧下肢无力，伴反射减退（前角和皮质脊髓束缺血）和病变平面以下痛觉和温度觉丧失（脊髓丘脑束缺血）。

（选项B）小脑后下动脉闭塞典型地导致外侧延髓（Wallenberg综合征）和小脑下脚缺血，导致吞咽困难、声音嘶哑和前庭小脑症状（例如，共济失调、头晕、眼球震颤）。{{exhibit_3}}

（选项C）虽然腰骶椎神经孔狭窄可引起单侧下肢无力，但此水平的脊神经根（下运动神经元纤维）的压迫损伤通常会导致明显的神经根性背痛和腿痛，伴有反射减退。

（选项E）大脑中动脉卒中主要影响上肢，通常伴有同侧偏盲、失语和半侧忽略。虽然大型大脑中动脉卒中也可引起下肢无力，但在这些情况下，缺陷通常很广泛，涉及上肢和下肢（偏瘫）。{{exhibit_4}}
